Really?  Are poems the only things that are poetry?  And is it even
possible, even given an emphasis on the visual, that poems *can* be
disconnected from flesh, blood, breath and tempo?  Or is there an
everpresent connection to these things that is merely reshaped by that
visuality?  Are painting, drawing and sculpture not connected to flesh and
blood, breath and tempo?  This paragraph makes me think of a lot of
questions (which probably should have remained unsaid).  Please elaborate, Burt.
 
Thanks,
Steve
