Damn, Mike, I cant remember the name of the woman who wrote it, but
it was really persuasive to me. It might have been a thesis at U. of
Toronto, say 7 years ago or so. She said that WCW sets up these (she
is mainly talking about the poems that look like, say, the poems in
CEP, ) poems that look as if they have regular short-line quatrains,
but read with different enjambments etc than the visual; says that
WCW was setting up the regular-looking and then forcing you to read
it differently, adding a complexity you might now expect. If I run
across her name I will send it along. There's a CHANCE that she's now
the woman teaching Williams-HD at Queen's, but that is a wild and
tenuous guess, sort of the way I was at my visual field test
examination at the eye care clinic this morning.
