Date:         Mon, 10 Jul 1995 11:36:47 -0400
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         David Kellogg <kellogg@ACPUB.DUKE.EDU>
Subject:      Re: Geoffrey Hill/Modernism & PoMo in England
In-Reply-To:  <00992BA3.67795980.19@met.co.nz>
 
In Ireland the fate of modernism is also very complicated, partly by the
overwhelming "International Modernist" presence of Joyce.  But certainly
the post-Yeats Irish poet who has gotten the most play in the States
(Heaney) could be called po-mo only by the most elastic of definitions,
and some of the most startlingly experimental (Devlin, Kinsella) are
barely read at all here.  Of course, McGuckian and Muldoon are relatively
well-known, but their language practices are tamed (and partly produced)
by American theoretical discourse.
 
Cheers,
David
