Date:         Wed, 12 Jul 1995 03:04:53 -0700
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Ron Silliman <rsillima@IX.NETCOM.COM>
Subject:      Re: teaching
 
I wish the old Grossman "A" 22-23 was still available. That would have
been the perfect teaching text for LZ (it's perhaps the best poetry he
ever wrote as well).
 
I had a great experience a year ago at Naropa working hard with the
students to define the core values of their own writing processes
(first a discussion of "how do you write" then one of "how do you
really write" that went into pen vs. computer, kind of paper, time of
day, location, whether other people were around, etc, etc, then had
them all write a single word on a 3x5 card of what, once you removed
all else, was the single thing you would find in their poems (my
favorite answer was "pivot"). Then I had them do work that left that
out (and which violated all the terms of their methodologies).
 
Teach what you don't know is a pretty good program
Write what you don't know is likewise
 
Ron
 
rsillima@ix.netcom.com
